{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a8d93f43-f86a-47e1-8b0d-14ce49cc3803","content":"Yes, these are known **MSTest v4 behavioral breaking changes** that compile cleanly but fail at runtime:\n\n---\n\n## 1. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it no longer has a meaningful `TestName` (it's `null`). Previously it was populated with the first test's name. This is by design; class init runs before any specific test.\n\n**Fix:** Don't access `TestContext.TestName` in `ClassInitialize`. If you need it for logging, use a fixed label or move that logic to `[TestInitialize]`.\n\n## 2. Discovery failures\n\nMSTest v4 enforces **stricter test-class requirements**. The most common cause: your `TestContext` property must be **nullable** or the class won't be discovered correctly under v4's new analyzer rules.\n\n**Fix for your file:**","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_cZ07WUcQq91nzpeeNOLCwS","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-551a48ac7b304e1ebab6fd7823d94185/DiscoveryTests.cs","old_str":"    public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }\n\n    [ClassInitialize]\n    public static void ClassSetup(TestContext context)\n    {\n        var name = context.TestName;\n        System.Console.WriteLine($\"Setting up for: {name}\");\n    }","new_str":"    public TestContext? TestContext { get; set; }\n\n    [ClassInitialize]\n    public static void ClassSetup(TestContext context)\n    {\n        // In MSTest v4, TestContext in ClassInitialize is class-level and has no TestName.\n        System.Console.WriteLine(\"Setting up DiscoveryTests\");\n    }"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-551a48ac7b304e1ebab6fd7823d94185/DiscoveryTests.cs."}],"interactionId":"f22533fc-3ed4-43d5-b9de-5fcbc8c77b1e","outputTokens":484,"requestId":"981A:1913CC:34F3D:44EEA:69FFF9E4"},"id":"b2a390c9-0bdd-4a52-b996-f3621cd285af","timestamp":"2026-05-10T03:22:24.902Z